{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01GxTrUzAisEbTfXGMywKwto","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The readiness probe is failing with a 503 status code on `/health?ready=1`. The issue might be that the `%3F` in the URL is not being URL-decoded properly. Let me check how the readiness probe is configured.\n\nThe issue is that `http://:http/health%3Fready=1` - the `%3F` is the encoded `?`. In Kubernetes probe spec, the `path` field should include the actual `?` not the encoded version. Let me check - actually the issue may be that the path `health?ready=1` in the Kubernetes HTTP get probe - Kubernetes does support query parameters in the httpGet path.\nLooking at the describe output, Kubernetes is URL-encoding the `?` in the path, which is a known issue with HTTP probes when query parameters are included. The 503 status code from CockroachDB's `/health?ready=1` endpoint typically means the node isn't ready to serve SQL queries yet, possibly because the cluster was just initialized and nodes are still starting up. or maybe the URL encoding is happening somewhere else). So the real issue is that CockroachDB is returning 503 because the nodes aren't ready yet after initialization—they need more time to fully join the cluster and become ready to serve SQL queries.\n\nLet me check the CockroachDB logs to see what's actually happening on the nodes.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":650,"cache_read_input_tokens":35210,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":650},"output_tokens":29,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e064f61f-de16-44d7-a275-88e070f04eaf","uuid":"dcb92294-9348-49c4-bbad-860cd909db2b","request_id":"req_011CcN3JyQXdZeMyTRgEypSn"}
